Sorry guys guitar strings don't move like that. It's the gd rolling shutter technique that the camera uses to film video at an acceptable frame rate. It's not like old film where it's 24-30 stills flipped through real fast, the next frame rolls down from the top of the screen and the movement of the strings is captured at different points in its oscillation. The "frame rate" of the camera acts like a strobe, catching instantaneous images of the vibrating strings. It works better outdoors because the sunshine doesn't flicker like artificial lighting, this giving a reference image that is continuous. The width of the oscillations is representative of the frequency but the mode shapes aren't correct.
I've seen this before, not this same video but the same kind of thing - amazingly cool. When you're actually playing the strings appear pretty much motionless!!

The "waves" we are seeing here are very, very short.  Makes me suspect they are an artifact of the camera more than anything else.  But they could be very high overtones, probably inaudibly high.  The fundamental (the note we hear) would have a wavelength twice the length of the string (or twice the distance from bridge to the fret at which the player's finger is pressing down).
